[1] Waterpark - USA (NY), norovirus suspected
Date: Fri 21 Mar 2008
Source: The Post-Star, PostStar.com [edited]
<http://www.poststar.com/articles/2008/03/21/news/latest/doc47e42f8f8280b851143779.txt>


State Department of Health officials still don't know exactly what
caused a gastrointestinal illness outbreak at the Great Escape Lodge
& Indoor Waterpark over the weekend, but the number of reported cases
of individuals sickened has risen to nearly 200. More than 300 people
have also called the department's hot line, (800) 278-2965, to report
symptoms of diarrhea and vomiting after visiting the resort or to get
information.

The Department of Health suspects a norovirus is to blame for the
sickness, but officials are still awaiting laboratory test results to
confirm that. This virus is usually very contagious, a Department of
Health announcement said, and is generally spread person-to-person by
direct contact or contact with contaminated surfaces.

While health experts await a definitive answer, Great Escape
officials seem to be taking more stringent measures to prevent the
illness from spreading. On Friday [21 Mar 2008], each person entering
the lobby of the lodge was approached by employees offering to squirt
sanitizer into their hands. An infectious disease specialist has also
been hired to consult with Great Escape on the situation. "They've
done everything the Department of Health has asked them to do, and
gone well beyond that," he said. "They sent out every piece of linen
from the rooms -- dust ruffles, pillow cases, sheets -- for outside
laundering. There was also one group of employees who worked in a
particular restaurant that got sick," Tack added. "So again,
proactively, Six Flags has closed that restaurant for 48 to 72
hours." (Six Flags is the parent company of Great Escape, and the
restaurant that was shut down was Tall Tales Tavern).

Tack said he doesn't believe it's likely that the employees or the
currently ill patrons got sick after eating contaminated food. "This
is not typically a food-borne illness," he said. "There's no evidence
this was food-borne at all. In fact, many of the guests who have had
this illness didn't eat in the lodge at all. The employees could have
contracted it, potentially, just by clearing a table or picking up a
glass, a plate or a fork," Tack added. There also isn't any evidence
that the illness was a result of tainted water.

"The water, both coming into the lodge and into the water park, has
been tested and has come back clear," Tack said. "This was not an
event tied to the water park's water or the municipal water coming
in." Tack suggested that the illness might have been brought into the
facility by a visitor last weekend.

Nevertheless, Great Escape isn't taking any chances with its sick
employees. Each staff member who is showing symptoms is being asked
to go home, and none are allowed to return until they've been better
for 48 hours, Tack said.

[Byline: Erin Demuth Judd]

