[2] Company HQ - UK (Scotland) - norovirus suspected
Date: Sat 22 Mar 2008
Source: The Press and Journal online [edited]
<http://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/Article.aspx/551474>


An international oil firm is expecting to find out today [Sat 22 Mar
2008] what was behind an outbreak of sickness and diarrhoea that
forced it to close its northeast headquarters. Marathon Oil UK sent
all staff at its Marathon House base in Aberdeen home on Thursday
[Thu 20 Mar 2008] to let NHS [National Health Service] Grampian and
council staff investigate the mystery bug which had struck down 100 people.

The firm, which has around 400 workers at the Rubislaw Hill complex,
said the decision to send staff home was made to stop the infection
spreading any further. An infection expert told the Press and Journal
the outbreak looked like the norovirus winter vomiting bug, which has
been rampant in the northeast, but the firm said it still did not
know the cause of the outbreak last night.

A spokesman said the firm hoped the results of tests would come back
at some point over the weekend. NHS Grampian's health-protection team
was called in to investigate the outbreaks, and members of Aberdeen
City Council's environmental health team were also at the offices on
Thursday [20 Mar 2008] to help with the cleaning of the site.
Marathon House will open again on Monday [24 Mar 2008], and it is
thought that all individuals affected by the bug are recovering at home.

NHS Grampian said anyone suffering from diarrhoea and vomiting should
be very careful with their hand hygiene and should remain at home
until 48 hours after their symptoms have settled.

[Byline: Ryan Crighton]

