Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[These 2 outbreaks of suspected norovirus infection are likely to be
confirmed as a consequence of their characteristic epidemiology.
Studies across the world have shown that in recent years most
norovirus outbreaks have been caused by strains belonging to a
particular genotype, named GII.4. The GII.4 strains evolve rapidly
(by mutation and recombination) and are further subdivided into
variants. Since 1995, 3 variants have emerged and replaced each other
globally, in 1995, 2002, and 2004. In 2006, 2 variants emerged that
co-circulated. Characterisation studies suggest that lineages evolve
through selective pressure and are likely to be antigenic variants
(drift variants). [see: Siebenga JJ, Vennema H, Renckens B et al.
Epochal evolution of GGII.4 norovirus capsid proteins from 1995 to
2006. J Virol., 81(18):9932-41, 2007; and ProMED-mail Norovirus,
strain characterisation 20080111.0146]. For these reasons, community
immunity is rarely built-up and retained. There is likely always to
be a high proportion of susceptibles in the population.

Noroviruses are highly contagious and often present as food-borne
infections through food-handlers and food premises. Fortunately, the
disease is short-lived, and thorough disinfection and attention to
personal hygiene can contain outbreaks, often before a definitive
diagnosis is established as in the outbreaks reported above.

Queensbury in New York state can be located in the interactive
HealthMap of the USA at
<http://healthmap.org/promed?v=40,-97.6,4>,
and Aberdeen, Scotland can be located in the interactive HealthMap of the UK at
<http://healthmap.org/promed?v=54.5,-2,5>.
- Mod.CP]
